<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,347,699]" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,491,518]" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">Description</emphasis>
. A small, threadlike species; 
<typeStatus box="[661,759,492,518]" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">holotype</typeStatus>
complete, 
<quantity box="[881,980,492,519]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.72" pageId="30" pageNumber="181" unit="mm" value="3.72">3.72 mm</quantity>
long, peristomium 
<quantity box="[1197,1269,492,519]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.8" pageId="30" pageNumber="181" unit="mm" value="98.0">98 µm</quantity>
wide; anterior, middle, and posterior setigers of same width, about 
<quantity box="[743,820,528,555]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.2" pageId="30" pageNumber="181" unit="mm" value="92.0">92 µm</quantity>
, last few setigers narrowing slightly; with 39 setigers. Anterior setigers about 1.5 times as wide as long (
<figureCitation box="[722,827,564,590]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">Fig. 19A</figureCitation>
); middle and posterior segments becoming somewhat rounded, as long as wide, with far posterior setigers weakly moniliform (
<figureCitation box="[954,1065,600,626]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">Figs. 19B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1075,1104,600,626]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="31.[151,250,957,982]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,189,930]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[151,1436,181,938]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 20. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287):A, anterior end through setiger 14, right lateral view; B, far posterior segments, dorsal view; C, posterior 3 setigers and pygidium, dorsal view. Stained with Shirlastain A." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269031/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">20</figureCitation>
B–C). 
<typeStatus box="[1177,1275,601,627]" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">Paratype</typeStatus>
(LACM-AHF Poly H360) smaller, broken in two parts, only 2.0 mm long with 20 setigers. Body cylindrical in cross section, with no dorsal or ventral grooves. Color in alcohol opaque white; no pigment.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="181" startId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" targetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" targetPageId="30">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1973,2034]" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,522,1973,1998]" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">
FIGURE 19. 
<taxonomicName authority="Blake, 2019" authorityName="Blake" authorityYear="2019" box="[295,457,1973,1998]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="30" pageNumber="181" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hessleri" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[295,457,1973,1998]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="181">Tharyx hessleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[464,522,1974,1998]" pageId="30" pageNumber="181" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269031/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" startId="31.[151,250,957,982]" targetBox="[155,1429,189,930]" targetPageId="31">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,957,1018]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,518,957,982]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
FIGURE 20. 
<taxonomicName authority="Blake, 2019" authorityName="Blake" authorityYear="2019" box="[293,455,957,982]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hessleri" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[293,455,957,982]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Tharyx hessleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[461,518,958,982]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end through setiger 14, right lateral view; B, far posterior segments, dorsal view; C, posterior 3 setigers and pygidium, dorsal view. Stained with Shirlastain A.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1064,2027]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
Pre-setiger region approximately twice as long as wide, slightly longer than first three setigers (
<figureCitation box="[1314,1432,1064,1090]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Figs. 19A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,204,1100,1126]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="31.[151,250,957,982]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,189,930]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[151,1436,181,938]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 20. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287):A, anterior end through setiger 14, right lateral view; B, far posterior segments, dorsal view; C, posterior 3 setigers and pygidium, dorsal view. Stained with Shirlastain A." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269031/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">20A</figureCitation>
). Prostomium triangular, tapering to narrow apex (
<figureCitation box="[787,903,1100,1126]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Figs. 19A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[917,969,1100,1126]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="31.[151,250,957,982]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,189,930]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[151,1436,181,938]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 20. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287):A, anterior end through setiger 14, right lateral view; B, far posterior segments, dorsal view; C, posterior 3 setigers and pygidium, dorsal view. Stained with Shirlastain A." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269031/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">20A</figureCitation>
); eyespots absent; nuchal organs not observed. Peristomium entire, smooth, without annular rings (
<figureCitation box="[823,927,1136,1162]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Fig. 19A</figureCitation>
); dorsal tentacles arising from posterior margin; first pair of branchiae arising immediately posterior and slightly lateral to dorsal tentacles (
<figureCitation box="[1229,1333,1172,1198]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Fig. 19A</figureCitation>
). Second pair of branchiae arising from setiger 1, dorsal to notosetae; subsequent branchiae from similar location. Branchiae present as stubs over anterior and some middle segments, not observed on posterior segments.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1064,2027]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
Parapodia reduced to low mounds from which setae arise. Setae of anterior segments all capillaries with 4–5 notosetae, including some long, natatory-like, continuing through middle body (
<figureCitation box="[1079,1197,1316,1342]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Figs. 19A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1212,1264,1316,1342]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="31.[151,250,957,982]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,189,930]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[151,1436,181,938]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 20. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287):A, anterior end through setiger 14, right lateral view; B, far posterior segments, dorsal view; C, posterior 3 setigers and pygidium, dorsal view. Stained with Shirlastain A." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269031/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">20A</figureCitation>
); capillaries of middle and posterior segments shorter, 4–5 per fascicle. 
<typeStatus box="[786,890,1352,1378]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Holotype</typeStatus>
with neuro-acicular spines first present from setiger 
<quantity box="[208,264,1388,1414]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.572" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" unit="in" value="18.0">18 in</quantity>
neuropodia and far posterior setiger 
<quantity box="[671,727,1388,1414]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.128" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" unit="in" value="32.0">32 in</quantity>
notopodia. Neuropodial spines typically numbering 1–2 at first, accompanied by 2–3 capillaries; in posterior segments notopodia with 1–2 spines and 1–2 capillaries, neuropodia with 2–3 spines and capillaries present or absent. Notopodial spines of far posterior segments longer than those in neuropodia, but both sets of spines emerging prominently from posteriormost setigers (
<figureCitation box="[1133,1246,1496,1522]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Figs. 19B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1258,1287,1496,1522]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="31.[151,250,957,982]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,189,930]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[151,1436,181,938]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 20. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287):A, anterior end through setiger 14, right lateral view; B, far posterior segments, dorsal view; C, posterior 3 setigers and pygidium, dorsal view. Stained with Shirlastain A." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269031/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">20</figureCitation>
B–C). Spines curved, geniculate, terminating in stubby knob-tipped apex (
<figureCitation box="[828,907,1532,1558]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
C–D); no denticles observed along shaft.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1064,2027]" box="[199,1392,1568,1595]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
Pygidium a thick rounded, ventrally directed lobe, surface with a coarse granular texture (
<figureCitation box="[1205,1318,1568,1594]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[159,1401,734,1944]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1409,720,1954]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287): A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, posterior end, dorsal view; C, neuroacicular spines; D, notoacicular spine and capillary." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269029/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Figs. 19B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1329,1380,1568,1594]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="31.[151,250,957,982]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,189,930]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[151,1436,181,938]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 20. Tharyx hessleri n. sp. Holotype (LACM-AHF Poly 11287):A, anterior end through setiger 14, right lateral view; B, far posterior segments, dorsal view; C, posterior 3 setigers and pygidium, dorsal view. Stained with Shirlastain A." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3269031/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">20C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1064,2027]" box="[199,775,1603,1631]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,431,1603,1631]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Methyl Green stain</emphasis>
. No pattern, de-stains entirely.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="182" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1064,2027]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1641,1667]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for Dr. Robert E. Hessler, prominent deep-sea ecologist whose pioneering work on deep-sea benthos, including collection of the 
<taxonomicName box="[761,837,1676,1702]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Echo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="31" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">ECHO</taxonomicName>
I samples reported in this study, has inspired generations of scientists.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="182" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1064,2027]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1749,1775]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Remarks</emphasis>
. Among the 15 described species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Webster &amp; Benedict" authorityYear="1887" box="[737,816,1748,1774]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[737,816,1748,1774]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Tharyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, only two species have been recorded from depths of 
<quantity box="[151,237,1784,1811]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000 m</quantity>
or greater: 
<taxonomicName authority="Blake, 1991" authorityName="Blake" authorityYear="1991" box="[368,668,1784,1810]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kirkegaardi">
<emphasis box="[368,525,1784,1810]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">T. kirkegaardi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Blake, J. A." box="[532,668,1784,1810]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" pagination="17 - 30" refId="ref19317" refString="Blake, J. A. (1991) Revision of some genera and species of Cirratulidae from the Western North Atlantic. Ophelia, Supplement No. 5, 17 - 30." type="book chapter" year="1991">Blake, 1991</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from off the 
<collectingCountry box="[819,868,1784,1810]" name="United States of America" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">U.S.</collectingCountry>
Atlantic coast in slope and abyssal depths to 
<quantity metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" unit="m" value="3000.0">3000 m</quantity>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blake" authorityYear="2018" box="[227,397,1820,1846]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="moniliformis">
<emphasis box="[227,397,1820,1846]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">T. moniliformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Weddell Sea in 
<quantity box="[679,767,1820,1847]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.086" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" unit="m" value="2086.0">2086 m</quantity>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Blake, 2019" authorityName="Blake" authorityYear="2019" box="[778,950,1820,1846]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hessleri" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[778,950,1820,1846]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Tharyx hessleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[957,1019,1821,1847]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[957,1019,1821,1847]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
from 
<quantity box="[1087,1172,1819,1847]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" unit="m" value="4500.0">4500 m</quantity>
is therefore the deepest recorded for any species of the genus. Both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blake" authorityYear="1991" box="[650,809,1856,1882]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kirkegaardi">
<emphasis box="[650,809,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">T. kirkegaardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blake" authorityYear="2018" box="[864,1036,1856,1882]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="moniliformis">
<emphasis box="[864,1036,1856,1882]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">T. moniliformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have serrations along the shaft and prominent knobs on the tips of the acicular spines thus providing a sub-bidentate appearance; in contrast, the knobs on the spines of 
<taxonomicName authority="Blake, 2019" authorityName="Blake" authorityYear="2019" box="[340,456,1928,1954]" class="Polychaeta" family="Cirratulidae" genus="Tharyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hessleri" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[340,456,1928,1954]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">T. hessleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[464,528,1929,1955]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[464,528,1929,1955]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
are rounded off, providing a worn appearance and there are no serrations along the shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,787,1999,2027]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1064,2027]" box="[199,787,1999,2027]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1999,2026]" pageId="31" pageNumber="182">Distribution</emphasis>
. Abyssal Pacific Ocean, 
<quantity box="[625,783,1999,2027]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.503" metricValueMax="4.506" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="31" pageNumber="182" unit="m" value="4503.0" valueMax="4506.0" valueMin="4500.0">4500–4506 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
